know_secure_design_justification: The development team works closely with Comcast security to review the application.
know_common_errors_justification: We regularly work on application requiring CSRF, CORS remediation.  Follow security best practices such as using TLS, disabling weak ciphers, not using TLS 1.0, and enforcing secure headers in our installations.
crypto_published_justification: Symmetric cryptography is pluggable, allowing users to implement their own.  Our default cryptography uses 256-bit AES with CBC/PKCS5Padding
crypto_call_justification: Our default cryptography leverages Java standard crypto
crypto_working_justification: We do not rely on any broken cryptographic algorithms in the product
crypto_password_storage_justification: We do not store user passwords
crypto_random_justification: Any keys we generate for the application use org.apache.commons.lang3.RandomStringUtils
delivery_mitm_justification: Application uses HTTPS and AWS SIG4 to sign all requests, preventing MITM attacks
delivery_unsigned_justification: We do not use the application over http
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: There are no vulnerabilities yet found
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: There are no vulnerabilities yet found
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: We use commercial software for static analysis internally at Comcast that are run daily
static_analysis_fixed_justification: No security vulnerabilities have been detected since open sourcing from our internal security scans
static_analysis_often_justification: We run static analysis daily, but internally as our software is paid (not FLOSS)
dynamic_analysis_justification: We currently are researching dynamic code analysis for securities.  We have run vulnerability tests at Comcast, all of the vulnerabilities identified pertain to the operation of the product, not the source code itself.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: We currently are researching dynamic code analysis for securities.  We have run vulnerability tests at Comcast, all of the vulnerabilities identified pertain to the operation of the product, not the source code itself.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: No source code security vulnerabilities have been found via dynamic code analysis
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: Use Travis for continuous integration - https://travis-ci.org/vinyldns/vinyldns

no_leaked_credentials_justification: The only credentials available are for testing

name: OpenImageIO
description: OpenImageIO is a library for reading and writing images, and a bunch of related classes, utilities, and applications.  There is a particular emphasis on formats and functionality used in professional, large-scale animation and visual effects work for film.  OpenImageIO is used extensively in animation and VFX studios all over the world, and is also incorporated into several commercial products. In addition to reading and writing many image formats, it also has an extensive set of functionality for image processing, out-of-core large image set management, a paging texture system, and many useful command line image utilities.

https://github.com/lgritz/oiio/blob/master/README.md
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: No vulnerability reports received in the last 6 months.
test_justification: No proprietary tools are needed to build the package or run the included testsuite.
tests_are_added_justification: CI tests must pass before PRs are merged.
tests_documented_added_justification: The github pull request template includes these instructions.
warnings_justification: We tend to use -Wall, with only a few warnings disabled (and as narrowly as possible) for cases that are clearly safe or that stem from 3rd party code that we cannot control.
warnings_strict_justification: We build CI tests with -Werr and -Wall (with only a few warnings disabled, generally to deal with 3rd party library issues).
know_secure_design_justification: The project leader is aware of these design principles and has read the above reference. Most of the principles are not applicable to this project, since it is not a web-facing app and there is no need for encryption, logins, authentication, credentials/permissions, or private information in the software's functionality. So we think that the level of awareness of these principles, as applies to this particular project, is sufficient.
know_common_errors_justification: The project leader is aware of these errors and has read the above reference. We don't claim to know much about most of these vulnerabilities, but on the other hand, they are almost all not applicable to this project, since it is not a web-facing app and there is no need for encryption, logins, authentication, credentials/permissions, or private information in the software's functionality. The primary classes of errors that lead to vulnerabilities (that are applicable to this package) are buffer overflow and use of unsafe library functions, and we think we understand those issues.

static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: clang-tidy tests include basic security-oriented tests.
static_analysis_often_justification: The static analysis takes too much time to run on TravisCI in its per-build allotment. We are working on addressing this so we can run static analysis on every commit.
dynamic_analysis_justification:
We currently have the per-commit testsuite on TravisCI run one test matrix entry with the build enabling "address sanitizer".
We don't yet use a fuzzing tool, but we plan to do so in the future.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification:
We currently have the per-commit testsuite on TravisCI run one test matrix entry with the build enabling "address sanitizer".

installation_standard_variables_justific: The result of the build process is a single binary which is installed in $GOPATH/bin/{executable} following the Golang convention. Our Makefile does honor DESTDIR
interfaces_current_justification: We periodically check and bump deprecated dependencies
automated_integration_testing_justificat: We use Jenkins with the Githull Pull Request plugin that triggers units, functional and advanced integration tests on a pool of slaves. The result is posted as comment on the Github pull reqestion
regression_tests_added50_justification: We don't allow any regression test
implement_secure_design_justification: The ACL mechanism by default forbids all actions by default. The default installation does not set up authentication by this process is straightforward and documented  https://skydive.network/documentation/deployment#configuration
